\title{Capability-Secured Neural Intent}
\taxon{definition}
\import{macros}

\p{The OCapN architecture applied to BCI. A decoded neural intent is a
\strong{capability}: an unforgeable, attenuable reference authorizing an action.}

\subtree{
\title{BCI-OCapN correspondence}

\table{
  \tr{\th{OCapN concept} \th{BCI interpretation}}
  \tr{\td{Vat} \td{Processing node (brain region, decoder, effector)}}
  \tr{\td{Capability reference} \td{Decoded intent with bounded authority}}
  \tr{\td{Attenuation} \td{Confidence-weighted intent (P=0.3 "move left" has less authority)}}
  \tr{\td{CapTP handshake} \td{Decoder-effector calibration protocol}}
  \tr{\td{Promise pipeline} \td{Predictive motor command issued before confirmation}}
  \tr{\td{Revocation} \td{Intent rollback on misclassification}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Safety through attenuation}
\taxon{remark}

\p{A misclassified "move arm" with confidence 0.2 should not have the same
authority as confidence 0.95. Capability attenuation gives this naturally:
the decoder issues an attenuated capability whose authority is proportional
to classification confidence. The effector cannot escalate beyond what
the capability grants. This is \em{not} metaphor — it is the correct
security model for invasive BCI.}
}

\subtree{
\title{CRDT brain state via Loro}
\taxon{remark}

\p{Multiple decoders (EEG, fNIRS, sEMG) produce concurrent state updates.
Loro's CRDT merge gives consistent global state. Text CRDTs for neural speech
output, structured CRDTs for hierarchical cognitive state (attention × valence
× arousal), version control for intent rollback. The brain state
\em{is} a CRDT: eventually consistent, conflict-free, mergeable across
modalities.}
}
